metadata.title: FONIO - User guide
metadata.subtitle: Step by step guide to using Fonio - September 2019

blocks.text: About

Fonio is a collaborative story editing tool designed for digital scholar dissertation writing, using the architecture of websites to structure your arguments. You can also incorporate various resources to enrich your work such as literature references, pictures, tables, videos and interactive elements. The tool was elaborated to encourage good practices in documentation and describe all the material used for your investigation (date, source, author, etc.). You can also build an extensive glossary.
Fonio allows for an in-depth informative design work. Find a way to enhance the reading experience and define your visual identity.
Several authors of a story can work simultaneously on the content, design and resources. (...) The classmates can read your work but only you as an author can edit the text.

Fonio was designed in the frame of the Forccast programme. Forccast is dedicated to pedagogical innovation for science and technology and controversies analysis. The tool was made in the médialab of Sciences Po. The medialab is a research lab whose area of investigation connects social science with new research, engineering and design methodologies.
Intended audience
The present guide covers all the basic features a first-time user needs to know to edit, organise and supplement the story with resources from the very first use.
Computer programming skills are not required to produce a high-quality story.
Here you will learn how to get started with Fonio from the home page.
1.1 Before you start
Fonio works with Google Chrome or Firefox, although we advise you to use Chrome for better stability.
Fonio saves you work on a remote server automatically and continuously. Access to the Internet is thus required.
You can access your story via its url from any computer.
For steps on how to export and save your story manually, see 7. Export and save your story.
Several authors can work on the same story. Yet to avoid problems during automatic backup, a lock system makes it impossible for several authors to work on the same section.
1.2 About the home page
You can change the language by clicking on [en/fr] at the top right of any page.
The [about] button (top right of the home page) gives you access to complementary information about Fonio.
1.3 Edit your profile
Click on [edit] by the avatar in the top-left corner : a window opens
Click on the avatar and select the one you like
Enter a name
Click on [Submit].
Note:
The avatar is useful to know who in your work group is online.
Click on [new story] in the top-left corner : a window opens.
Complete your story meta data : title, subtitle, password, authors and story abstract
Click on [create story] to validate : the introduction section is created and opens automatically.
Note :
You can add as many authors as you like.
Keep your password, or you will not be able to edit your story in the future!
You must share the password with all the members of your workgroup.
You can edit the story settings at any time from the [Contents] tab (top left in the menu): your story overview/ summary opens.
The text you edit in Fonio is structured in sections and subsections. As a reminder, the introduction section is created and opens automatically when you create a new story.
3.1 Create sections
Click on [Contents] in the top menu bar (to open your story summary).
Click on [New section] : a window opens
Complete the metadata in the window open
Click on [Create and start editing] : the section page opens.
Notes:
You can create as many sections as you like: click on [Contents] to get back to the summary and follow the same procedure.
You can change the section metadata from the section page (see 3.4)
3.2 Change the order of sections
You can change the order of sections from the page of a section :
Click on the blue triangle at the top left corner of your section page to open the summary
Click on the UP or DOWN arrows to move a section up or down.
3.3 Change the level of the sections
From the overview (summary), you can change a section level to create a subsection.
Click on the blue triangle on the top left corner of your section page to open the summary
Click on the RIGHT arrow to level the section down : the section becomes a subsection.
Note :
There are only two levels.
You can also change the order and level from the [Contents] page (top menu bar)
3.4 Edit the section metadata
Open a section
Click on the section title
Click on the pen icon that appears to the left of the title : the metadata window opens
Edit and click on [save changes]
Advanced users can write in markdown language. It is automatically converted into text when you validate the entry.
4.1 Add text to sections
Open a section: the cursor is automatically placed in the text box
Write your text
Click outside the grey text box to validate the entry.
4.2 Change the text formatting
4.2.1 Put your text in bold or italics
Select the text you want to format : a menu appears.
Click on [B] or [I]  to put your text in bold or italics
Notes:
If you want to cancel the text formatting, click on the icon again.
You can also click on the bin icon to cancel all the formatting.
4.2.2 Insert a numbered or bulleted list
In case you want to write all the items of the list in the first place, you need to break the line after each item.
Select the items you want to put into a list : a menu appears
Click on the numbered list icon or bulleted list icon.
4.2.3 Change the title level in the text
This feature allows you to create a title level (1 or 2) in the existing text.
There are only two levels.
Select the text you want to put as title 1 or 2
Click on [T] to create a level 1 title or [T] to create a level 2 title
4.2.4 Insert a quote
Select the text you want to put between quotation marks
Click on the quotation mark icon
4.3 Add hypertext links
Hypertexts links can point distant resources (e.g. link to a press release) or other sections of your FONIO story (i.e. I want to refer the reader to the first section of the present user guide).
4.3.1 Add a hypertext link to a website
Select the text
Click on the blue link icon that appears
In the windows open: copy and paste the link to the distant resource in the URL field
Click on [add hyperlink].
Note:
You can click on [Choose an existing hyperlink] if your link is already stored in the Library, and select the link in the drop down list.
Links to distant resources appear in blue in the text.
4.3.2 Add a hypertext link to another section of your story
Select the text
Click on the green link icon that appears
Click on [choose a section]
Select the section in the drop down list that appears
Click on [add a section link].
Note:
Links to other sections appear in green in the text.
4.3.3 Add a link to a glossary entry
Select the text
Click on the purple link icon that appears
Define a new glossary entry or click on [choose an existing glossary entry] if applicable
Click on [add entry].
Note:
Links to glossary entries appear in purple in the text.
4.4 Add a note
Place the cursor where you want to insert a note
Click on the star icon that appears to the left of the text box
Write the note
Click outside the text box to validate the entry.
Note:
The features in the Design tab (top menu bar) allow you to change the note position (side note of footnote - see  6.Configure the Design ).
You can enrich your text with a variety of resources (items) :
pictures,
videos,
tables,
code (particularly useful to insert a distant content),
references,
hyperlinks,
glossary entries.
Note:
Except for notes and hyperlinks, you cannot insert an item directly in the text. You need to add it to the library beforehand.
It is of paramount importance that you include the sources - you are legally responsible for your public productions.
5.1 Add an image to the library
Make sure to edit the picture size BEFORE adding it to the library.
The picture appears in the story in the size you have defined. If it is too big, the size adapts to the width of your screen.
The maximum file size permitted is 3Mb.
Click on [Library] in the top menu bar
Click on [new item] in the top left corner : resources icons appear
Click on the image icon
Click on [Drop an image file]
Select the image on your computer and open it: a preview of the picture appears in FONIO
Complete the fields : Title, source, author.s, date of publication, description as exhaustively as possible
Click on [add image].
Note :
Only pictures and tables in csv or tsv format are local resources, i.e. you can upload them in the library from your computer.
5.2 Add a table to the library
For advanced use, you can create a table in csv or tsv format and add it to the library.
To add a table :
Click on [Library] in the top menu bar
Click on [new item] in the top left corner
Click on the table icon
Click on [Drop a table file]
Select the table on your computer and open it: a preview appears in FONIO
Complete the fields : Title, source, author.s, date of publication, description as exhaustively as possible
Click on [add table].
5.3 Add a video to the library
As a reminder, video is not a local resource - you need copy-paste the video url from a website.
YouTube and Vimeo are the only platforms you can upload your videos from.
To add a video :
Click on [Library] in the top menu bar
Click on [new item] in the top left corner
Click on the video icon
Copy and paste the video url in the field "Url of the video"
Complete the fields : Title, source, author.s, date of publication, description as exhaustively as possible
Click on [add video].
5.4 Add html code to the library
As a reminder, programming skills are not fundamental to produce a good-quality story.
This feature can be useful to embed a third-party content in the text, for instance a tweet or a SoundCloud file.
Here again, it is important to specify the source.
Here is an example of code integration with a Graphcommons graph:
Click on [Library] in the top menu bar
Click on [new item] in the top left corner
Click on the code icon
Open Graphcommons
Copy the share code of the graph you want to add
Back in Fonio, paste the graph code in the box "Embed code"
Complete the fields : Title, source, author.s, date of publication, description as exhaustively as possible
Click on [add code].
5.5 Add a reference to the library
You can add a file in bibtext format which contains one or several literature references.
For advanced use, you can use a bibliography managing tool like Zotero, and export your references in bibtext format to add them to the Library.
For basic use, you can add a literature reference in the text and create a bibliography section, or use the note or glossary features.
Click on [Library] in the top menu bar
Click on [new item] in the top left corner
Click on the reference icon
Add your bibtext file (.bib)
Click on [add references].
5.6 Add a hyperlink to the library
Click on [Library] in the top menu bar
Click on [new item] in the top left corner : resources icons appear
Click on the hyperlink icon
Copy and paste the hyperlink URL in the URL field
Complete the information fields : the title you choose will appear as such in the text.
Click on [add hyperlink].
5.7 Add a glossary entry to the library
Click on [Library] in the top menu bar
Click on [new item] in the top left corner : resources icons appear
Click on the glossary icon
Complete the fields "Glossary entry name" and "Glossary entry description"
Click on [add glossary entry].
5.8 Add an item in the text
There are two ways of inserting an item in the text.
Option 1 (from a particular section):
Open the section which you want to add an item in
Place the cursor in the text where you want to insert the item
Click on [+] that appears to the left of the text box: a drop down list opens
Click on the item you want to insert.
Option 2 (from any section):
Click on the blue arrow in the top left corner to open the summary
Click on the section in which you want to add the item : the section opens
Click on [Library] (to the right of [Summary])
Drag and drop the item where you want it in the text.
Note:
You cannot move an item once it has been dropped. The first option is thus preferable.
Fonio allows to publish a story as a website made by default to be clear nice to use. You can also configure a specific design, in accordance with your story identity and the use of reading.
Click on [Design] in the top menu bar.
The Design page is divided into two parts:
your story overview on the right,
the control panel on the left.
The control panel is divided into two tabs:
[Settings],
[Styles].
6.1 Change the design from the [Settings] tab
6.1.1 Choose the template
Fonio allows you to present your story in two default templates :
"garlic": a single-page layout allowing to play with scroll-based interactions.
"pepper": a multi-page layout allowing to play with hypertextuality,
The templates define both the visual organisation of the pages and the navigation process for the readers.
The default styles of the templates can be configured in the [Styles] tab.
6.1.2 Choose the cover image
The cover image appears on the front page of your story once published and gives your website a visual identity.
Upload a cover image in the library
Click on [Design] in the top menu bar
Click on the drop down menu below "cover image"
Click on the cover image: the change applies automatically.
6.1.3 Change the notes position
The position is set as footnote by default.
Click on the drop down menu
Select the sidenote or footnote feature: the change applies automatically.
6.1.4 Change the figures position
There are two ways of displaying the figures (images videos, advanced blocks (code) and tables):
relative to scroll : the figure appear to the right of the text as you scroll down or up, to make your story even more interactive.
in content body : the figure are integrated into the body text.
To choose either of the features :
Click on the drop down menu below "Figures position"
Click on the feature of your choice: the change applies automatically.
6.1.5 Change the type of items to display in the references

Fonio automatically generates a references section in your web rendering, with a view to trace and document the elements used in your story. By default, literature references cited in your story are the only resources to appear in the references section.
To choose the type(s) of resources  (images, literature references, videos, etc.) to display in the references section (online):
Click on [choose item types]: a drop down list appears
Click on the type(s) of items to display in the references: they are highlighted in blue (click again to cancel the choice).
Click outside the list to validate your choice.
6.1.6 Choose the resources to display in the references
You can choose specific resources to display in the references:
all the items listed in the library
the items cited in the text only
Select the option in the drop down menu.
6.2 Change the design from the [Styles] tab
6.2.1 Change the story background color
Click on the palette icon to the right of background color: a color list drops down
Click on the color of your choice: the change applies automatically
Click on the palette icon again to close the list
Note :
The feature "Define background opacity" works with a cover image only. You cannot change the background color opacity.
Drag the circle to the left or right to define the cover image opacity.
6.2.2 Change the size and color of the cover text
Click on the drop down menu below "Cover text style"
Click on the size of your choice: the change applies automatically
Click on the Palette icon on the right and select the color of your choice.
6.2.3 Change the size and color of the titles
Click on the drop down menu below "Title style"
Click on the size of your choice : the change applies automatically
Click on the Palette icon on the right and select the color of your choice.
6.2.4 Change the size and color of the body text
Click on the drop down menu below "Body text style"
Click on the size of your choice : the change applies automatically
Click on the Palette icon to the right and select the color of your choice.
6.2.5 Change the size and color of quotes
Click on the drop down menu below [Blockquotes styles]
Click on the size of your choice : the change applies automatically
Click on the Palette icon to the right and select the color of your choice
6.2.6 Change the color of links
Click on the Palette icon to the right of "Links styles": the color list drops down
Click on the color of your choice : the change applies automatically
Click on the Palette icon again to close the list.
6.2.7 Edit CSS styles
Advanced users can enter a CSS formula in the code field "Edit styles with CSS" to change a design feature.
You can copy the formulas on a CSS code sharing website and paste them in the code field. The changes will apply automatically.
You can also edit the styles using the formulas in the help window :
Click on [help] below the code field : three code formulas appear
Click on [add] to the right of the formula you want to apply (you can add all of them) : the formula appears in the code field
In the code field, change the colored word or number to modify the feature: the change applies automatically
If you wish to know more about CSS basics, have a look at this tutorial.
As a reminder, Fonio saves your work automatically and permanently, but you still can export your story in three formats :

Html for publishing (folder): the format of your story when published. It is not modifiable, though useful if you want to view your website offline. This export option allows you to download a folder, that contains a comprehensive website optimized for access on any browser.

Html for archiving (single file): all-in-one format. It is not modifiable, though useful if you want to view your website offline. This option provides a single file easier to archive, although less adequate for publishing, especially if your story contains pictures.

JSON for back-up (single file): the format of your story that is still modifiable and mainly used as a safety back-up. In case of loss or deletion of your story, you can reimport the JSON file into Fonio.
7.1 Export your story
You can export your story from any section or the summary of your story.
Click on [export] at the top right
Choose the export format: the file is downloaded and stored in you computer’s Downloads by default
7.2 View the story in the browser
In the "file" menu of your browser, click on "Open the file..."
Double-click on the file nameofyourstory.html (in your Downloads folder): the story published opens in the browser.
7.3 Reimport a JSON format into Fonio
Go back to Fonio’s homepage
Click on [new story]
Click on [import an existing story]
Drag and drop or double-click on the JSON file to reimport it : the story opens
Note:
From the FONIO homepage, you can visualise your story in Fonio by clicking on [read] (in the control panel to the right of your story). This feature does not export the story in html format.
8.1 Export your story for publication
Once complete, your story is ready to be published online. To this end, Fonio allows you to export your story as a static   website.
To export your story as a static website (from your summary or any section):
Click on [export] at the top right of the page
Click on [export your story to publish it]: an archive folder .zip is downloaded
Double-click on the .zip folder to unzip it: you get a folder containing the website ready for online publication.

The website can be published online on a variety of digital infrastructures (your own website for instance). It is also designed to be easily published on shared web hosting services, two of which (Netlify drop and GitHub) are presented in detail below.
8.2 Publish a website on Netlify drop
Netlify is a platform to support the publication of websites.
Go to Netlify drop
Drag and drop your website folder on "Drag and drop your site folder here"
You website is online! To make it viable and customize the URL, you need to create a (free) Netlify account.
8.3 Publish a story on GitHub pages
With this platform you can host, version and publish code on the Internet for free.

CMS solutions (e.g. Wordpress) are largely oversized for the publication of a website with a few pages. Furthermore, they require specific hosting, technical knowledge to complete the setup and medium or long term maintenance.
GitHub pages allows you to publish your story online and share it freely in five minutes.
Please note that any story published becomes public.
To install your website on GitHub :
Create a GitHub account (free)
Create a GitHub folder (repository) : you can later access it at https://github.com/YourLogin/YourRepositoryName
In FONIO, click on [export...] and [export the story to publish it]: a zip folder is downloaded
Unzip the folder
On GitHub, click on "upload an existing file" (picture 1)
Transfer all the files from the unzipped folder to your GitHub repository (picture 2). This may take a little while.
Make sure the feature "Commit directly to the master branch" is ticked (picture 2)
Click on [Commit changes] (picture 2)
Click on [Settings] (top right in the menu bar - picture 3)
In the "GitHub Pages" section, click on [branch] and choose "master"
Your website is now accessible at yourUserName.github.io/myRepository

A static website consists of a set of pages made with standard web technologies (HTML, CSS, javascript). It does not require a complexe, technical architecture using database for instance. This enables to publish robust websites that require minimal setup and maintenance procedures.
